I recently purchased a Cocoon Create Touch. It will print ABS, unlike my Deltaprintr. But it is way too cold here at the moment so it needed a cover. My junk pile has lots of old TV and Ham radio antennae so I cup lengths of the tube to make a frame and covered it with bubble wrap.
Print 6 x FrameCorners, 2 x TopFront1 and that is the box. You could just print 8 x TopFront1 corners instead as I did. The only difference is the extra hole for the front DoorTop to hang in.
1 x DoorTop and another but reversed.
2 x DoorBTM and the front door is done.
The pins on the DoorTop parts sit in the holes of the TopFrame1 parts.
Another option that I have not done yet is a swinging door.
2 x DoorHinge for the swinging side and 2 x DoorBtm.
Then on the box, have 1 x FrameHinge2 and another swapped to have the door clip into.

A flap cut in the bubble wrap allows access to the controls, and a clear bit of plastic packaging makes a window.
NOTE!! I "measured" the tube to be 9mm but it is actually 10mm so I had to drill the sockets out. Scale it to suit your dowel or aluminium tube.

This is a quick fix to allow me to print ABS and it appears to work. A slot cut in the wrap on top gives access for the filament. Clear plastic could be used all around. It is all held together with clear wide sticky tape. Not quite Duct tape, but you could use that if you want ;)

Plant pot with water reservoir.

I decided to design this plant pot with inbuilt water reservoir compartment to saving my time and keeping my plants healthy. Due to inbuilt water reservoir tank, now I don’t need to watering my plants frequently and also plant roots growing healthy due to excess water draining to reservoir.

When you print this 3D model, your 3D printer will have to extrude lines of plastic between already printed parts from the bottom section, in the way that I design the bottom section of this model, the plastic bridging lines won’t fall down when being printed. If you see your 3D not printing bridging, you may need to fine tune your 3D printer to print best bridging results.

When you fine tune your 3D printer for printing bridging, please consider lowering printing temperature (A temperature between 180 C and 200 C should work well for PLA). Also tuning your print speed also important.

When I design this model I have to consider your 3D printer bridging capability. So, I have added special design feature to support 3D printer bridging capability. Due to this special design your 3D printer will print plant pot’s water reservoir compartment without overhanging excess plastic.

description.text:
I thought that the Nautilus gear spinners were great, math in hand (logarithmic spiral, and what should be a Fibonacci sequence for the shell partition spacing although maybe it isn't) and they printed well. But when I handed one to my wife she put it down after a second - the hardware I used stuck out of the thing and irritated her hands - it was sharp everywhere, it seemed. She suggested I redesign the connector and so I did. I do most of my design work, such as it is, in openSCAD. This was no exception. I built disks thick enough to allow the hardware to be completely countersunk. I made everything parametric. I have uploaded the stl files - but there is one extra - it seemed that two gears just were not enough - so I included stl files for a bar that will connect four gears. You can use the scad file to build on that if you want to, I have sort of wondered if a hexagon would close properly. Once I got the two bars as I wanted them it was easy to add more since it was just a matter of calling routines I had already written.

To give credit where credit is due, the nautilus shell objects are completely taken from the object I remixed from, without change. The only change I made was to the connectors. The shells have always printed well, and on my printer, the largest one needs a little heat to let me insert the bearing. If the bearing does not fit fairly easily, do not try to force it. The bearing retaining wall is thin and it will crack. Use a little heat from a hot air gun or even your heated bed, cover the object with a metal or glass cup and heat it until it is just sligltly plastic (but too much heat will cause the object to be deformed). You can do that if you don't have anything else, heat just until you are able to insert the bearing. It should be firm but not forced.

In the photo, you can see a double and a single bar in PLA and the yellow single bar is printed in PETG. I have yet to try one in ABS, but the tolerances are critical so I worry about shrinkage.

Edit: OK, I couldn't help but thinking that many of the other mixes of the original Nautilus used split bars so that you could more easily see the gears mesh. And it was not hard to create such a bar in openSCAD. In fact, I made a square bar and the same code worked for an oval bar (probably not strictly elliptical, although it is regular.

I have included a sample set of STLs for the styles. All of the styles can be generated by the new openSCAD I downloaded and you can probably even generate a four position bar if the values for the space between the slit bars is not too high.

Printer:

HE3D K280

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Should print at 0.4mm nozzle and 0.2mm layer

Infill:

30% or 50% for stiffness and strength

Notes:

Using a brim is not recommended unless you absolutely needed, and do not get the first layer too tight so that it spreads. I also suggest printing one of the two nautilus gears (or two of the four) with a mirror flip so that any printing tendencies get reversed and they fit together better.

You will need to print two (or four) of the nautilus gears of your choice and two bars, a "screwbar" and a "nutbar" or you can grab the openSCAD file and modify those to your needs for the hardware you have.

Dimensions are critical. Too tight or too loose will cause the thing not to function or to function poorly.
If you print this without a brim or raft and with an accurate first layer, no post processing should be needed at all.

openSCAD requires you to think in basic shapes and how to warp them. In this way, it is sort of like Tinkercad, but, unlike Tinkercad, once you do something it becomes a building block that you can reuse. It was fairly simple to do that to build the initial connector bar - to add cylinders, subtract cylinders (for the countersink and screwhole) and to add a connector bar. But the second requirement was not to have sharp edges where fingers went. So I used a minkowski sum routine to create roundovers and because the bar on the item I remixed was keystoned, I made mine keystoned, and used a minkowski sum to round the edges of that. It was actually a simple routine to do, relatively, and faster to do this way than through something like tinkercad where it is difficult to create accurate center-to-center distances.

But there are two benefits - if you need a bar that is a little longer or shorter to accomodate your printer, you can download openSCAD, and modify the openSCAD file (all those parameters are set up at the file beginning. Or say you want to use one of those threaded inserts - just change the diameter and number of facets on the "nut" side, and maybe the depth of the inset.

I have been wondering if it would be possible to create the nautilus gear in openSCAD. I have seen the maple routine. Not sure if openSCAD is up to it. Have to create a very complex polygon, extrude it, and round it over.

Hardware required

1 608 bearing for each nautilus shell. (2 or 4 as shipped).
1 3mm allen head screw, 14mm long, for each nautilus (2 or 4, as shipped).
1 3mm nut, plastic insert preferred, for each nautilus. (This should be a pattern by now, 2 or 4 s shipped.)

"Such is a dream of light,
But to float upon a sea of clouds" An idea I've been toying with for the better part of 3 years now, I have finally realized in a printable sculpture. This Is my lighthouse poised on a floating island. I made it for Mother's Day so as to give my mom a gift that was from a personal place, while making new use of an old trope: isolation of the lighthouse. I made the original file in sketchup, and have included the file for your use. Please enjoy.

The file comes in 3 parts. Simply print out all of the files. I found that no shells and 60% infill was good for the top, 1 shell and 25% infill worked for the bottom, and no shells, 40% infil was good for the base. all three prints in succession will be about 5 and a half hours. Once printed find a nail that fits the holes in the base and bottom of the island depending on however large you've scaled the print (diameter is all that matters really, native size is a little bigger than 3mm) and place it in the bottom of the stand. To adhere the top of the island onto the underside, I recommend brushing acetone onto both surfaces, lining them up, and then holding them together for a few minutes. The acetone essentially welds the to parts together. After that, just place on the nail, and enjoy! one might consider painting it or flocking some grass onto the top, or adding scale trees. Native print size is about 1:720 scale. 
Alternately, if you prefer lighthouses sans floating islands, then you can print only the top part and do what you will with it.

description.text: Angle connectors and magnet holders for a cheap 3D printing chamber frame. Connectors are made for 10x10 mm and 15x15 mm wood bars (length depending on your printer dimensions). Use a cover made of plastic foil and Scotch tape, and use 4 mm neodymium magnets for closing the front flap door.

Printer Brand:

Printer:

Rafts:

Yes

No

Resolution:

0.30

100%

Notes:
  • ABS is recommended rather than PLA to allow better elasticity.
  • 100% infill is highly recommended to prevent angle connectors from breaking.
  • Before printing you should perform the Part Fitting calibration https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2372705

Introduction

In order to ensure quality 3D prints and minimize the risk of finding a Spaghetti Monster waiting for you in the printer, you should enclose a printer in a chamber that stabilizes the temperature. When printing with ABS, such a chamber is absolutely a must!

Prusa i3 MK2 chamber Required Parts
Mandatory
  • ABS angle connectors (printed) - 8 pcs
  • 10 x 10 mm or 15 x 15 mm wood bar (I used 10x10 mm) - length depending on your printer dimensions, generally around 7-8 meters
  • Transparent plastic foil (2-3 m², do your math for your own printer)
  • Adhesive tape 2-2.5 cm wide
Optional (for magnet flap door)
  • ABS magnet holders (printed) - 4 pcs
  • Neodymium magnets Ø4 mm x 2 mm - 12 pcs
Taking Measures

Measure width, depth and height of your printer. Allow a few centimeters on each side for easier access and to allow the bed to move back and forth. Do not forget to take the spool into account!

Bar dimensions for my Prusa i3 Mk2
  • Width (sideway bars): 50 cm
  • Depth: 55 cm
  • Height (vertical bars): 62 cm
Assembling the Chamber

Carefully cut the bars to the required length and connect them using the 8 angle connectors to make a cubic frame. The bars should fit tightly into connectors. Loose is no good! Use a file or sand paper if the connectors are too tight, or print a single connector for a test, playing with the scale a few percents up or down. Once you find a perfect measure, print the rest of the parts.

Vertical bars should enter inside the holders to have their top side aligned with the top side of the connector.

However, you might want to push the bottom side of the bars a few centimeters pass the bottom side of the connectors, to allow some space for cables. I left 3 cm for "legs" on my Prusa chamber.

Vertical bars enter into holders all the way on the top The vertical bars go a few centimeters pass the bottom connectors, to allow some space for cables Allow some space on the bottom for cables Magnet Flap Door (optional)

If you want to have a front magnet flap door, which is definitely something I'd recommend, do not forget to put the two magnet holders on each side on the front vertical bars, before you assemble the bottom holders.

Force the magnets into the holes using a vice, but first put a bar inside to prevent squishing the connector. Beating a magnet with a hammer is a bad idea, since it will weaken the magnet force. The magnets go into the 4 magnet holders, and 2 go on the front side of the bottom connectors. That's 6 pieces on the frame, plus 6 pieces for the door.

Assembled frame with the front magnet holders (right side of the photo) Magnet holder Wrapping Up

Carefully tailor the foil to cover the frame. Allow a few centimeters on each side to wrap around the bars, and fix it with Scotch tape, straining it properly.

Leave the front door connected just on the top side, so it could be flipped on top. Strain in slightly over the magnets and place 6 magnets to hold the door in place.

title: Optimal Heatbed Level System (OHLS)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This Thing is for an optimized bed leveling with thermal barrier.

Description
The Peek cylinder serves as a thermal barrier to prevent the heat from the heat from the heating bed into the printing table. Because the two screws are screwed into the cylinder, they do not have a direct transition to one another, and the heat is hardly transmitted through the pekk because it has a very poor thermal conductivity. At the same time, however, the peek is very heat-resistant and the temperatures of the heating bed can be very well tolerated.
The silicone damper is used to adjust the pressure bed and, in combination with the Peek part, provides a more stable structure than would be the case with a spring. In addition, the silicone does not have any direct contact with the heating bed due to the peek, which is why it is not so quickly degraded by the influence of the temperature and becomes porous.
The screws can be selected according to the circumstances. Why this system can be used with almost every printer.

Parts

  • 4st Peek Cylinder 12mm*8mm and M3 thread insite
  • 4st Silikon damper (Make them with the mold)
  • 4st M3 Screws of your choice for the heatbed
  • 4st m3 Screws of your choice for the table and adjusting

This 3-piece object comprises a handlebar-mounted fixture that will securely hold a Samsung Galaxy S4 phone in the perfect position to use during your ride.  Great for using a map application to navigate, a music app to feed your headphones, or a workout app to track your ride.  Or, of course, you could also actually talk on the phone.  
Note:  The tray-shaped part that holds the phone was the difficult part of the design; it can be easily adapted to other applications by designing your own mount, allowing you to put your S4 pretty much anywhere.  My son, for instance, made a music stand mount so he can use a metronome app while practicing sax.

(1) Print the two files (three parts). Clean them up as necessary. Make sure your phone fits snugly into the tray; it should snap in with an audible click. Release the phone by pulling back the tab at the bottom, then pushing the phone out with your finger through the hole in the bottom of the tray. (2) The two handlebar-mount parts form a ring that fits snugly around the handlebar of your bike. One of the mount parts has a flat surface; glue this to the back surface of the tray part in a place that puts the phone where you want it relative to your handlebars. Note: By far the best way to glue these parts is by printing them in ABS and then using ABS cement to make the joint. This will actually weld the parts together and produce a joint that can't fail, ensuring that your phone remains securely attached to your bike. (3) Get two 4mm x 20mm bolts and two 4mm hex nuts. Put the nuts in the nut capture openings in one of the handlebar mount parts. Put the bolts through the other handlebar mount part and screw them together around your bike's handlebar where you want it. Tighten things down securely. Add a thin layer of rubber sheet or electrical tape between handlebars and mount if your mount needs extra grip. (4) Stick your phone in the tray, and ride!

description.text:
UPDATE: Added two variations on the coil for someone who wants to use it for a screwdriver antenna. It should measure out to be about 50uh. It has a plain interior because I believe that the center should contain supporting structure such as a piece of ABS plumbing pipe, or a wooden dowel epoxied in place. The bending load on something this long will be considerable, so better interior support will definitely be required.

NOTE: Updated. Removed Glue Together assembly instructions. If you downloaded the files before Midnight on Monday May 29th, you may want to re-download the files to get the newset version. Please read the instructions below for the latest assembly instructions.

This is a loading coil for the fold-up PRC Antenna pictured. This antenna is very lightweight, and when horizontal, it only droops about 4 inches. It is 113.5 inches long (2.88M). The AT-271 "Fishing Pole" antenna was used on the PRC-25 and PRC-77 Squad Radios and also on the PRC-104 HF radio. A number of commercial radios also use the AT-271. See http://www.prc68.com/I/AT271.shtml for more details.

The antenna, with all 7 sections extended, operates at 25Mhz.

This Loading Coil at 22uh should bring the operating frequency into the 40M band (7Mhz). I designed it to be 25uh total, so you can easily fine tune it by shorting out a few coils with a clip to one end.

No

Notes:

I printed this in PLA at 0.100mm layer thickness so that it would print the overhanging spiral grooves without needing any support. When printing at 0.200, i found that support was required to keep the extrusion from drooping in the overhanging grooves.

If this will be exposed to the elements for extended periods, please print with a UV resistant filament. PLA will be ok for occasional outdoor use, but will not handle the elements well.

A UV resistant ABS is the preferred filament for strength and it's ability to withstand long periods of exposure to sunlight and weather.

I found that Princess Auto sells a nice 16 Gauge galvanized fencing wire that works nicely with this coil form. Wind it on the coil as tightly as possible with about 3" (60mm) of wire on the inside of the WireForm to attach to the end contacts.

Place the insulator into the Wireform. Insert the end of the wire into the hole on the side of the insulator, (do this for both ends of the insulator before screwing the threaded brass 3/8-24 rod or tube into the insulator) then screw the ends of the threaded rod into the insulator. Carefully tighten down on the wire, then snip off the excess wire. Place the end caps over the threaded rod and press them into the WireForm until fully seated. Optionally, you can put a 55mm diameter x 2.5mm O-ring on the cap to provide a seal. Or, you can put a bead of RTV Silicone around the cap and let it cure before assembling everything. Secure the end caps with a Low Profile 3/8-24 nut. The low profile nut will sit in the hexagon shaped recess in the end cap. Rotate the end cap to tighten. Lubricate with silicone grease to assist assembly and provide a better weather seal. Be careful not to over tighten them and damage the 3D printed end caps or insulator. 3D printed parts can be fragile and excess pressure may break the end caps, or pull the insulator apart. Cut the end of the threaded rod to be 1/2 inch (12mm) beyond the end of the nut. This will provide enough room on each end for the next section.

On one end, use another low profile 3/8-24 nut to secure a 6" length of stranded wire with an alligator clip at the end. (silicone wire is best for flexibility) Then put a long 3/8-24 nut on one end to act as the Female connector for the fold up antenna. I use hanger bolt joiners (available at Home Depot). They're a little long at about 1 1/4" long, but they work suitably.

You can get Ultra Flexible Silicone insulated stranded wire at Hobby King

  • 2V => 21.98 grams

The files I included contain all shots taken during the test, with 6 text files that have all the airfoil coordinates used in the build, the printable STL files and finally the SLDPRT files. Should you want to have some fun with the propeller, make sure you get a couple of 8520 coreless motors.

title: Drela AG18 Airfoil Micro Drone Propeller (36.61g thrust @ 3V)

description.text:
This propeller was inspired and designed by using the Drela AG18 airfoil coordinates. All tests were done on the Micro Drone Propeller Thrust Testing Jig (test results below).

It was printed at a slow speed, using a 0.2 nozzle at 0.04mm height per layer. I cleaned the final part with the help of a Precision Knife

After this, I got to finishing the part with a 400 grit sandpaper.

These are the thrust measurements for some voltage presets (you can also view these in the images):

  • 1.5V => 11.9 grams
  • 2V => 22.41 grams
  • 2.5V => 31.12 grams
  • 3V => 36.61 grams

The files I included contain all the pictures taken during the test, along with 6 txt files that contain airfoil coordinates, the printable STL files and finally the SLDPRT files. If you'd like to have some fun with this propeller, you should get a few 8520 coreless motors.

You can use the SLDPRT files, in case you want to make your own changes to the propeller.

Note: The airfoil plotted by using the matplotlib library in python.

description.text:
This egg always stand vertically once you release it. It contains at the bottom a 5/8" or 16mm metal bearing ball that shifts its center of gravity close to its wide bottom.

I printed it in its vertical orientation with material support only from the printing bed (that is, no material support inside the egg). When it completed to print the internal cylinder I paused the printing, dropped the ball in, and added some glue from a hot gun (epoxy or any similar glue should also be fine), and then un-pause the printing.

When the printing completed, I cleaned up the bottom with an X-Acto knife and sand foam sponge to round the bottom. Then balanced it by placing on a flat and smooth surface, observing the orientation and sanding slightly the side of the bottom that is too high (the egg tilts away from the high side().

PLA, 0.2mm, material cooling fan on, 30mm/s, support from printing bed only (not inside the egg).

description.text:
A differential assembly I've been making as a component for my machine. When I get my bearings through the post, I may redesign for those, but it works surprisingly well with just washers :D Bill of materials:
0.2 mm nozzle (at least that's what I used)
0.1 mm layer thickness (again, what I used)
to print:
One of: DiffBase_x1.stl
One of: DiffCap_x1.stl
One of: Separator_x1.stl
Two of: DriveGears_x2.stl
Two of: LooseGears_x2.stl
I print all of these with raft, and exterior support only. 3mm steel (or sufficiently stiff) shaft. two of arbitrary length, and one of 30 mm. eight, 3 mm washers. some thin copper wire (I stripped mine out of a network cable).

Instructions are attached in images. The only thing to note is that holes often don't print at exactly the right diameter - you may need a 3 mm drill bit just to ream out some holes. Just don't ream out the drive gears! They're meant to be stiff on the shaft! Also, the separator (the small cylinder with crossing bores) has been designed to have a push-fit on the 30 mm shaft, but be loose fitting on the drive shafts. The push-fit isn't vital, but the loose fit on the drive shafts is. The gears were generated with the OpenSCAD script http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3575/

title: Motor Saver Coupling Adjustable Torque Limiter

description.text:
Update: 1-28-14 Added .IPT files for your use and updated to v3 that includes some design refinements (tweaking tolerances) and set screw nut slot on input base. Recommend printing v3 files.  
Update: 1-27-14 Added four holes on the CUP, just tap threads, insert bolts/screws, place washer inside CUP and add spring or small rubber piece, stack torque adapter atop spring, snap the base into the CUP, adjust bolts to set torque.  
This is a motor coupling with 8mm shaft openings. This coupler is designed to slip when a certain torque is reached.   
The torque limit is set by adjusting screws or installing different springs (size and strength) between the cup and adapter.

Install on 8mm shafts. Pick your spring (start with a lightweight one first) or small piece of rubber hose, pick out your bolts or screws, tap the four holes in the CUP, install screws, place washer in the CUP, install spring, insert adapter in the cup, Snap the cup assembly into the base and adjust screws/bolts to the torque needed.   
I have tested with PLA using active cooling at 100% infill at .2 with supports.

Notes:

I used Grey, White, and Black PLA filament.

I had to scale it 75% of the original design in the slicer program to fit on my 200mmx200mmx180mm printer. 

<<<<<<<<< IMPORTANT >>>>>>>>>

EVERYTHING MUST BE SCALED TO 75% TO PRINT ON A 200mm 3D PRINTER!

<<<<<<<<<<<<<<<>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>

Pieces Needed (Quantity):

Grey Filament
(1 ea) Base
(1 set) Support Arm pieces (five pieces)
(4 ea) Attack Board Dowels

White Filament
(3 ea) Field Boards
(4 ea) Attack Boards
(8 ea) Pawn
(2 ea) Rook
(2 ea) Knight
(2 ea) Bishop
(1 ea) Queen
(1 ea) King

Black Filament
(26 ea) Black Squares
(6 ea) Black Corner Squares
(8 ea) Pawn
(2 ea) Rook
(2 ea) Knight
(2 ea) Bishop
(1 ea) Queen
(1 ea) King

5 Minute Epoxy was used to bond pieces together. Dynatron 650 Glazing and Spot Putty was used to fill and smooth pieces. A Fill and Sand Primer was used to smooth base and support arm then painted with Krylon Metallic Gold spray paint. Aluminlite Clear Cast Epoxy was used to finish the board and pieces.

TIps:

  • TEST FIT EVERYTHING BEFORE BONDING!

  • Print Base, Support Arm pieces, Attack Board pegs and Attack Board dowels first. The larger pieces take a long time to make and finish. You can finish them while the other pieces print. I used grey PLA.

  • Print the boards and a set of chess pieces first. This will minimize your time. You can start to finish parts while others are being printed. 

  • Duplicate the Chess pieces in your slicer program to print one job for each kind of piece. Example: Print 8 Pawns at once, print 2 Rooks, etc.
     

  • Match fit all Support Arm pieces together BEFORE bonding. Pieces should fit nicely but due to printing variations, some pieces may not fit or align perfect. Sand and test fit them. 

  • Use 5 minute epoxy to join the support arm pieces. Work 1 joint at a time. Try to keep it aligned as straight as possible. Don’t worry if not perfect. 

  • Once epoxy is fully cured on Support Arm, check alignment of the piece. The place where the boards will go should be parallel to each other and should be straight. If not, place in a warm oven (use the warm setting or the lowest it can go) for a few minutes then correct shape. BE CAREFUL AND WATCH IT CLOSELY. It’ll melt your part real fast. You have to work quickly to get the Support Arm into shape before it cools.

  • While you still have the oven warm, put in the Attack Board Dowels in there for a few and fit to the pegs. They should fit snug when cooling. You’ll have to sand a little to loosen them for a smooth fit. You don’t want any wobble in there. 

  • Lightly sand Black square edges to fit onto Field Board. Use a few drops of superglue to lay them in place. 

  • Bond finished Field Boards one at a time to the Support Arm. Wait until each board is fully cured before moving onto the next. 

  • Lay the board upside down and flat then attach the Support Arm to it. This will greatly help keep things in place while the epoxy cures. 

  • (Optional) Finish everything in epoxy coating. Careful not to coat the peg or inside of the dowels or use too much epoxy on the pieces. A good thin layer of epoxy will give you a smooth, durable, and shiny finish.

Design

I used AutoDesk Fusion360 to sketch up and fit the design. I printed a few trials to get the Support Arm right since it was the biggest piece and because it needed to be accurate and able to support the boards.

New improved version: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2800717

More info: https://hackaday.io/project/25092-zerobot-raspberry-pi-zero-fpv-robot
Video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=16rxNzQvfYY&t=4s
Raspberry SD Image: https://hackaday.io/project/25092-zerobot-raspberry-pi-zero-fpv-robot/log/62102-easy-setup-using-sd-image

ZeroBot is a Raspberry Pi Zero W based robot. It can be controlled using any computer or smartphone via a web browser. The integrated camera module makes for a low latency video stream. In addition the Raspberry Pi acts as a Wifi access point, so no router is required. The parts for the hull as well as the wheels can easily be printed on any regular 3D printer.

Some of the key features are:

  • Compact CAD design with 3D printed components
  • Analog control via a joystick (and multitouch)
  • Simple battery solution using only a standard power bank
  • Low latency streaming (~0.3s)
  • Easy and cheap to build using widely available components

Print the two shells with the inside facing the print bed. You will need to include a lot of support material. Simplify3D works best for this, but Slic3r or Cura with optimized settings should be fine as well. I used support with lower density for the most part and higher density for the last 8 layer up to the part. This saves a lot of filament.
The tires should be printed with Ninjaflex or something equivalent to ensure good grip.
Everything else can be printed in PLA.

Glad you like it! And thank you for your suggestions.
Just yesterday I read about someone powering their Pi with 3.7V. Now I have looked it up:
A PMA2306 regulator (https://www.diodes.com/assets/Datasheets/PAM2306.pdf) creates the 3.3V and 1.8V that the Pi needs internally.
The input for this regulator is the 5V USB plug, but it will accept much lower voltages as well. At 3.7V the processor will run just fine but the USB port will not be powered.
This is kind of a hack but should not be a problem as long as you don't use the usb or hdmi ports.
Right now I am working on an improved version of the robot which will have a software shutdown button in the user interface.
And the new parts have a usb charging port and a hole for an LED.

description.text:
This is a wallet with a money clip, and a slot for a USB flash drive.

Other than the obvious wallet-y features, the design goals here were:

  • Cover the cards as much as possible, to avoid damaging their edges
  • Hold a USB drive, to let me remove the one I was carrying on my keychain
  • Avoid sharp edges, which were apparently abrading holes in my pockets

Known flaws, after carrying it around for a bit:

  • The money clip's clearance against the wallet body is too loose, single bills don't clip well
  • The money clip spline's nearest point to the wallet body is too far out, folded US currency doesn't sit flush against the spine while under the clip
  • The radiuses along the edges of the piece create a thin wall that eventually split. I'll redesign this and address this issue in the next version.

Notes:

The print orientation needs to make the "grain" along the money clip, to avoid splitting when it's flexed. So that really only leaves 2 orientations.

I printed this one with the "card hole" side down, with support. It might equally work with the "USB hole" side down, but the support material might foul the usb socket.

To start, I counted the cards I've been carrying around, and used a pair of calipers to measure their combined thickness. The standard credit card specification (found online) has accurate values for the width and length, but I assumed (correctly) that the stack dimension would be different from the sum of the specification's thickness, due to the embossing they do for the card numbers.

Next, in Fusion 360, I drew out a stack of cards, and also a sort-of-accurate model of the SanDisk drive linked above. This drive had a sort of swoopy feature on the handle that made that difficult, so it was a lot of trial and error with the calipers.

With these two models the "card box" was just an offset box around the cards with a 1.5mm thick wall and radiused corners. I measured my thumb with calipers for the "ejection slot" width, but it's not very critical.

The drive holder in the spine started as another solid block, big enough to contain the drive. I then moved the drive model inside the block and subtracted it, to get a tight fit. To ensure the drive slid out properly, I moved it out half way and subtracted again. Then with those dimensions captured, I "cleaned up" the slot to reduce the geometry, keeping the tight fit around the drive socket end.

The money clip was entirely a freehand spline that "looked about right". In hindsight this eyeballing ended up with the least well-designed part of the whole piece.

This prop is designed to be printed in ABS and hooked together using acetone for a secure bond.

The prop consists of a total of 8 printed pieces (the files included represent one half of the prop, so will need to be printed mirrored for the other half) and two ~5mm diameter rods of any material you choose (I used wood because it was able to be trimmed to length easily, and was still much stronger than a 3D printed rod, so the prop can go into a holster or conventions, display, etc, without breaking).

File Directions:

01-02 Mal Rod End – the end caps that go on rods. No supports needed if printed flat. This file does not need to be mirrored, simply print 2 copies.

03-04 Mal Half Barrel – this is half of the barrel and front sight. If your printer does half-circular shaped voids well without supports, you can print without; if you’re not sure, I recommend using supports. This piece needs to be printed twice, once normally and once mirrored.

05a-06a Mal Half Main – this is the main portion of the prop. It requires minimal supports, but they are needed. This must also be printed once normally and once mirrored. This is the version of the main body I have printed and used; another version labeled 05b-06b Mal Half Main Flared Grip has a grip that has is flared out at the bottom, and is closer to the original grip that the non-flared one. I have not printed or used this file, but I include it here incase others want to.

07-08 Mal Half Rear Sight – these are the rear sights that are fixed to the back of the prop. They will need supports. One printed normally, and the other mirrored.

This is a super simple micro-servo gimbal designed for use with the with the GoPro Hero 3 and Hero 2.  
The micro-servos press into their parts and are screwed in through the back. There is a small slot for the arms that allows you to embed the connections with hot glue. There is a also a hole through the pieces allowing you to screw in the servo arms to make a strong connection.   
It has no trouble lifting and controlling the Hero 3 and feels very stable. I've made it very generic to allow you to use any camera that can fit. I tried to make it compact and light as possible.  
The top plate for connecting to your quad can be modified however you like, I recommend drilling out holes before attaching so you don't split the print.  
I plan on using it for my 330mm quadcopter, but it can be adapted to any use!

I used adafruit micro-servos: https://www.adafruit.com/products/169 Print at 20% infil. You'll also need hot glue or epoxy to attach the servo arms to the subsequent piece. Remember to put your servo at 90deg before attaching the arms to allow full rotation. (left: 0 - 90deg right: 90-180deg)

description.text:
A very simple delta frame design using only 2060 extrusions and a single type of bracket!  Hence the name Delta One.  I plan to use this easy design to create my delta printer.  A single Misumi 2060 is cheaper than using 3 x 2020, yet it is much stronger.  The idea behind using 2060 is that it is overall more cost effective to achieve a very solid delta frame.  Also this design does not disable the mounting versatility of the extrusions at each corners.  Therefore, designing motors/idlers/rails/smooth rods brackets are all modular and open to different requirements.  The bracket is split into 2 pieces for each legs so that even the smallest printers should be able to print it.  
Updated with design B.  It is now symmetrical and bottom mounting holes are countersinked.  
Updated with design B1.  Made the inner dimensions whole numbers.  Fillet the outer corner.  
Updated with design C.  Made a 1 piece design for larger printer.  
Updated with design D.  Reduce materials.

For half brackets, print a total of 12 brackets.  Total number of 2060 extrusions needed: 3 x legs and 6 sides of whatever size you want.  Typical sizes would be 1000mm legs and 300mm sides.  Mounting holes are all 4mm.  Print volume required: X-100mm Y-60mm Z-70mm.  
For full brackets, print a total of 6 brackets.  Print volume required: X-160mm Y-60mm Z-70mm.
